review_blob: 22 oz. bomber. Sharp, somewhat astringent aroma. Nice shiny copper color. Underactive head. Kind of a sweet and sour type brew that seems to be attempting a balance of opposing forces. It doesnt quite make it. The hops dominate and not in the best of ways. Theres not enough behind the hops to carry their strange presence in this beer. The Spot series just gets weirder with each entry.

12oz. can. Pale yellow and transparent, with an  active head on the pour. The head fades fairly quickly and leaves minimal lacing. Aroma is mostly citrus with some resinous pine in the background. Taste is mostly citrus, grapefruit and tangerine, and overpoweringly so, as it really wreaks havoc on the palate. Perhaps the Summit hops are not to my taste, but this seems overdone. Theres not enough behind the bitterness to carry it properly, especially onto the back of the tongue for the finish. Its kind of like POP! and youre done. Its an ok brew, but for OB repeats, its still Ten-Fidy and Gordon.

12oz. bottle. Fairly flat pour, yet decent lacing. Aroma is heavy on the grassy hay side with a touch of honey. The flavor is understated for a winter seasonal, dry and a touch on the sour side. Makes me wonder if there is rye in the mix. A little bit flat on the back of the tongue, so the finish is kind of weak. The alcohol is well hidden. I almost want to say this is more of a fall beer than a winter. And it would be only a fair to middling fall beer.
beer_name: Southern Tier Old Man Winter Ale

review_blob: 22oz. bomber 09 release. Pours completely flat, a hazy dark amber color. Nose is honey/caramel sweet. Flavor improved with warmth, but was still overly fruity and sweet, lacking a solid hop structure. The alcohol (10.1% listed on this bottle) is pretty well hidden by the stuff that is there. That stuff, however, is a little off-kilter. Im not sure this will age well, but it might be worth a try.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: 22oz. bomber bottle. Slightly hazy yellow color. Minimal head and little to no lace. The aroma is dry and hoppy, with nothing really special standing out about it. The hops kind of pile on top of the flavor--theres some citrus and some pine. However, theres very little underneath the hops. The finish in particular vanishes rather quickly. Theres an interesting hop profile here waiting for something a little more substantial to carry it. The alcohol does hide pretty well in the mix.

24oz. bottle. Outstanding spicy floral aroma. Puffy beige head stayed atop the beer forever, leaving thick lace. Reddish gold in color--a very pretty beer. Taste is sharply tart, full of spicy citrus hops. The malt presence is a deeply buried semi-sweet, almost rooty backbone. The flavor clings to the tongue, but never presents anything off-balance. This has been one of my favorite beers!
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Harvest Wet Hop IPA - Northern Hemisphere

review_blob: 12oz. bottle. Slightly opaque golden color topped by a fairly active head that dissipates a bit quickly. Aroma is of bready malt with a faint touch of hay. Flavor is typical for the style, perhaps just a bit too sweet. The hops do appear more fully on the back of the tongue. Mouthfeel seems a little thin to me, but Ive already been drinking winter seasonals this year! This is a pretty good O-fest, but Ill stick with the German brewers for the best.

12oz. foil-topped bottle. Very little head on the pour. Murky golden color. Aroma was on the sweet side, which was a little troubling for a brew aiming to be a hop monster. More hops are present in the flavor, thank goodness, although there is still a lot of malt sweetness pervading. Allowing the beer to warm a bit after pouring does cut this impression a bit. Theres a fair amount of citrus and pine tang on the back of the tongue, but the overall mouthfeel is just a bit lacking. I wonder if letting this one sit for about 4-6 months might help it out a bit. Not bad, but needs some refining.
beer_name: Grand Teton Lost Continent Double IPA

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle. Autumn-gold color. Nice head, though not long-lived. Bread and butter on the nose, which works its way into the flavor as well. Sweet honey notes. Not much tang from the hops. Mouthfeel is a little lacking. Its a drinkable O-fest, but not on my list of favorites.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Bottle. Beautiful amber color and active head on the pour. Aroma was weak, though it carried hints of macro-brew. Flavor is very much corn/macro--too sweet and yet too weak at the same time. No body to speak of. Its not offensive or anything; its barely there at all. Too bad this beer couldnt live up to its appearance.

12 oz. bottle. Dark brown/black with a beige to tan head. Head is active at first, but fades pretty quickly. Little to no lace. Nice dry flavor, with nuts, caramel, coffee and a hint of chocolate. Mouthfeel is a little weak--I want just a little more chewiness in there. Finish is dry with some hop bitterness. Very nice overall. Had it at the brewery several years back while on vacation. Thanks to the in-laws for bringing some back from their vacation. Though they dont drink, they loved the food at the brewery. Good job, SRB!

22 oz. bomber. Leathery brown color, slightly opaque. Great head at the start, but not much lace. Aroma is definitely spicy and rich. The flavor and palate impression are a big disappointment. I expected more peaty smokiness, and a little more malt sweetness. The finish is too sour and metallic on the tongue. Ive tried this twice to rule out mishandling, and wont be going back for thirds.

12oz. bottle. Pours a really deep amber color, topped with an active head that fades fairly quickly. Not a lot of lace. Flat, faintly metallic aroma is not incredibly inviting. Very dry, hoppy flavor for an amber, and not much of a finish. There are some things to like here, but this turns out to be one of Stones weakest offerings.

12oz. bottle from 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Transparent gold, frothy white head, plenty of lacing. Clean, sweetish aroma with a touch of citrus. Hops are more piney in the flavor profile, along with sweet, doughy malts. I thought it was a little light on the palate for an IPA, but its still rather tasty. Nice, slow finish that easily invites the next swallow. Fine stuff!

12oz. bottle. More of a traffic light amber than copper, the color is still pleasing. The head is active for a few seconds, but is quickly gone. No lace. The aroma is light, with some hops citrus and a touch of sweet grass. Flavor is not overly malty, given the amber style, with more hoppiness than most ambers. Drinks pretty smoothly; lagering probably helps that. All in all, a pretty respectable beer.

On tap at the Parkway in Tacoma. The keg blew as my beer was poured, so factor that in. Orange, slightly hazy color. Lots of pine and citrus aroma and flavor. Sweetness is almost overdone, as a bubblegum tang hits about mid-tongue. The alcohol was very well hidden. Plenty of hops here, but its not in the hop-monster class. The Amarillos have never impressed me much.

On Nitro at the Parkway in Tacoma. Magnificent presentation in full cascade, served at just the right temperature. Completely opaque black color, with a creamy beige head. Excellent lace. Roasty mocha nose, and an even deeper flavor following. Its a dry stout, but with a touch of extra hops and malt that add so much to the flavor. Great beer made even more enjoyable on nitro. Thanks, Parkway!

22oz bomber. Pleasing pour into my Leavenworth Grumpy Old Ale snifter. Opaque dark leather brown color, topped by a nice, smooth tan head. Uneven lacing, but its there. Aroma is stuffed with hops and dry chocolate. Taste and mouthfeel are really off-style for a barleywine, mainly due to the predominance of the hop profile. I really like this beer, but it really doesnt fit into my conception of a barleywine. It seems more like a high-test winter warmer or holiday ale. Hey, what difference does a category make? Its tasty stuff!

12oz. bottle. Pretty pour into a snifter. Very active tan head initially that fades to a heavy ring and center film--great lace. Chocolate-black color is totally opaque. Aroma is muted, faintly smelling of roasty coffee and cocoa. Dry on the tongue, the flavor is mocha and a touch of raisin and hazel nut. Not a hefty body, and the finish is little weak, but this is tasty porter, overall.

.5liter swingtop. I always look forward to doppelbock season, re-try my favorites, and see what new ones manage to get into the local bottleshops. This one has a great frothy pour and attractive deep garnet color. Aroma is faint and doesnt present much complexity. A faint whiff of banana is the strongest impression I got. Flavor carries some hint of smoke and a peach/plum character. There is really no finish to speak of. All in all, a drinkable, but forgettable doppelbock.

.5liter bottle. dark, reddish brown color, not quite transparent. Minimal head leaving no lace. Strong, sweet aroma carrying lots of fruit. Flavor is strongly plum/raisin on a float of brown sugar/molasses. Slightly lacking on the back end for flavor, although the aftertaste is pleasingly sweet. Id buy it again. Its possible I started this one out a little too chilled.

12oz. bottle from 99 Bottles in Federal Way, WA. Love the bottle presentation, although the micro-text on these stone offerings is getting to be a bit much for aging eyes. Its that much worse on a small bottle! Semi-active pour, beige head that fades away fairly quickly and leaves minimal lace. Compelling, spicy nose, with the sage and juniper rising to the front. Spices in the flavor are wonderfully subtle, all perfectly balanced and complementary. Great peppery hop bite on the back of the tongue. Really hides its alcohol well. Just a great brew. Im going to try to get more for the aging cache.
beer_name: Stone / Jolly Pumpkin / Ngne  Special Holiday Ale

review_blob: 22 oz. bomber. Pretty pour, with a decent head, both initially and in longevity. Some good lacing. Aroma is dry candy (think Necco wafers) and whiff of pine and hay. Flavor is intensely grassy, with a sharp, grungy bite along the sides and back of the tongue. The finish is pretty clean, mostly resinous pine and a hint of citrus. That middle of the mouth WTF drops this offering into my "its ok" category. Though not bad, its a bit disappointing.

12oz. bottle. Very pretty pour, with an active head, though that doesnt stick around too long. Nose is very subtle, with just hints of coffee and bakers chocolate. Flavor is just as understated--not sweet, not bitter--seems like almost nothing really jumps out at you. Yet, its not an unpleasant brew at all. Lawnmower stout?

22 oz. bomber. Pours smooth, a cool clear copper color with an active head that falls away swiftly. Nice spicy, malty nose. A little sweet on the uptake, with the hops following along to cut into the soft underbelly. A totally drinkable strong winter ale.

12 oz. bottle. Fairly frothy head leaves a touch of lace. Dark red-brown color is not quite opaque. Nice hop spice and bite all along the tongue. Full of maltiness, but not overly sweet. Finish is bitter with a hint of roasted nuts and spice. Definitely a winter mainstay. You have to check this one out every year.

On tap at the Harmon Hub. Pint arrived with almost no head, and there was no lacing to speak of. Color was a dark suede brown. Nice nose to this brew, full of mocha and dark sweet sugars. Flavor is massive dark bitter chocolate, with the bitter holding out against the sweetness very nicely.  A touch of coffee also tempers the mix. Really well-done beer! Served well as dessert.

12 oz. bottle. Great mahogany color and huge puffy head--a really pretty beer. Spicy, nutty, and surprisingly hoppy for a winter warmer. Excellent finish with a flavor that really sticks around. Purchased at 99 Bottles in Federal Way, and I got my beer club T-shirt today! What a great store!
beer_name: Laughing Dog Cold Nose Winter Ale

review_blob: Completely black pour into a snifter produced very little head. However, the foam that appeared was scarcely lighter than the beer! Chocolate/coffee dominates both nose and mouth. Very thick on the palate initially, but is not cloying at all. Probably a perfect balance between sweetness and bitterness. I would never have purchased this had it not come recommended by fellow beer drinkers I trust.

12oz. bottle. I remember the W06 red ale, though I wasnt rating beer at the time that came out, and I dont religiously take notes like I should. This is not a traditional seasonal style, although Sierra Nevadas Celebration is comparable. The body here is very light, and given the alcohol content, that can mean trouble. I recall the W06 as being hoppier. Celebration ages nicely, and Im going to try cellaring some of this. Hopefully theres enough hops to carry it down the road.

On tap at the Parkway Tavern in Tacoma. Cloudy dark yellow in appearance. Nice head if poured properly ( a few rounds came brim-full, which is nice for value, poor for tasting.) Great up-front hop bite, backed with really sweet malts. Melony, bubblegum fruit flavor is quite apparent, but theres a lot of bittering working along with that sugar. The Celebration is much drier on the tongue than this brew. I really enjoyed this one.

12oz. bottle. Slightly cloudy gold in color. Aroma is a bit muted, with a tendency toward grain and grass, rather than the typical yeasty fruit and spice of most hefes. Flavor has a touch of banana/clove, but is a little too light on the tongue. All that being said, its a nice summer brew, probably tuned toward swaying American tastes. I do appreciate this brewerys efforts, but Im glad I have some Ayinger Dunkel as backup.

Sampled at 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Grassy aroma. Sweet grass and hay flavor profile with just a hint of hop-citrus bite. A very middle of the road IPA. Although the info here indicates 6.5% alcohol, the in-store literature read 5.5%.

Sampled at 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Intensely malty nose chock full of nuts, honey and herbal notes. Flavor was totally nutty, more of the sweet filbert/almond essence than the astringent walnut/pecan character. A stand-out ESB in my book--truly distinctive.

Sampled at 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Called a Vienna Lager, I think it lacks some of the malt backbone to live up to that label. However, its got very solid malt body, and tangy hop bite. Its light to be sure, but nicely drinkable.
beer_name: Grand Teton Au Naturale (Organic Blonde Ale)

review_blob: On tap at the "Christmas in July" event at the Parkway Tavern in Tacoma, WA on 7/3. Served in 9 oz. schooners, the beer arrived with no head and left almost no lace. Aroma was loaded with caramel, coffee, and stone fruit (plum was my dominant impression.) This brew in no way resembles the mainstay Black Butte porter. Its far sweeter, heavier, and stickier. Chocolate, coffee and plum/apricot sweetness dominate the tongue. The hops are nearly lost in this barrage. There wasnt a lot of bourbon presence in this one, but just enough to make things interesting. I imagine this would cellar extremely well. Hope to find a bottle or two somewhere.

22 oz. bottle from 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Massive head on the pour, leaving near perfect lacing. Orange/gold color is completely transparent. Aroma is pretty understated for an IPA, revealing more of the malt than the hops. Plenty of hops on the tongue, and a nice, sticky resinous body that allows the hops to really coat the mouth. Like many of Full Sails IPAs, this one is very herbal and especially grassy. I enjoyed this beer, and would get it again.

On tap at Maritime in Seattle. Red-gold in color. Slight maple/caramel aroma with just a whiff of hops. This is a sweet one, though perhaps less so than other maibocks that Ive tried. Still, the sweetness seemed sticky, nearly overpowering some of the other characteristics of the brew. The alcohol shows up after a few sips, and its presence grows as the glass empties. Drinkable, but a wee bit out of balance.

Nitro pour at Maritime in Seattle. Deep copper color, fluffy head with perfect lacing. Just a bit sweeter than the typical ESB. The hops swept evenly along the tongue however, balancing out the maltiness rather well. I wanted to sample this non-nitro, but other brews beckoned. Ill just say: if you can sample this on nitro, do it that way. Really tasty!

22 oz. bomber. Vibrant, copper/amber pour with an active head. Nice lacing. Sweet, malty pine/spruce nose is not overwhelming, but rather enticing. Flavor tends toward the malts over the hops, although the bitterness builds over the back of the tongue and into the throat. Nothing is overdone here except the overall product. A really well-balanced brew. Youll feel the alcohol later, but its well-hidden in the drinking.

12oz. bottle from Tacoma Boys Market. Minimal head on the pour, some lacing, and a tawny leather color. Aroma is massively sweet with stone-fruit overtones. Flavor is also sweet, but nowhere near where the nose was indicating. A smooth, honey-like mouthfeel helps to prevent the sweetness from becoming cloying, as do the hops. Good hop profile really pushes this brew above and beyond. Let this sit about 15 minutes out of the fridge, and itll be right where you want it. This is really what youd call a barleywine. Deschutes doubled down on their Mirror Pond (Mirror Mirror) and this really compares very  closely.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: 22oz. bomber. Somewhat dirty brass colored pour. Not a lot of foam, and no lace. Strong grapefruit/citrus aroma and flavor. The hop varieties seem balanced, but there is not an overpowering bitterness. The beer really begins to shine as it warms just a bit, so dont go ice cold on it. Very nice IPA.

22oz. bomber. Pale gold color, with a nice smooth head on the pour. Active carbonation provides a good ring of foam, but not much lace. I was surprised to see that this recipe was the same as Yellow Snow. The juniper character is very mellow, both on the nose and tongue, so those who dont like herbal beers should not shy away. Rogue is pretty good at keeping their accent flavors under control (chipotle and the memorable rose petal beer for example.) This is a very drinkable beer, but is somewhat unremarkable. It does seem a bit watery and the grassy, herbal flavors are not supported well by the body of the brew.

500ml bottle from Tacoma Boys Market. Huge head on the pour, but dissipated rather quickly. Enticing aromas of bread, clove, and maple/caramel. Not overly sweet or hoppy, this is a perfect example of the style, and I love this style. No, its not done often enough in my opinion. If its going to be hefe, make mine a dunkel.

22 oz. bomber from 99 Bottles in Federal Way. Active, foamy pour leaves layers of lace. Amber in color, with just a touch of haze. Nose is a sweet pine and citrus mix, strong, but not overpowering. Flavor is malty for an IPA, but perhaps not for an IIPA. In this case, I felt that the malts kind of pushed some of the hop bitterness aside. Even so, the hops are present all along the tongue, and do leave a lasting impression. The mouthfeel is definitely thick and resinous. Those looking for a hop-monster might be disappointed, but I liked this beer quite a bit

22 oz. bomber. Nice head on the pour, leaves perfect lace for at least half the glass. Garnet red color is completely clear. This is a great looking brew! Aroma is strongly malty, caramel mapley sweetness, and this carries right on through to the flavor. Overbearing sweetness is this offerings downfall. Its like the juice-box of barleywines, without anything to balance it out. Almost no finish to speak of. I guess you might try to cellar some to see if it eats some of that sugar over the years, but I have some doubts.

22 oz. bomber. Active head on the pour, and plenty of lace all the way down the glass. Tawney red-gold color is just slightly hazy. Slightly spicy grass aroma, with just a trace of pine and citrus. Malts are a little on the sweet side for an IPA, but I think this adds some character and interest to the brew. Mouth feel is a little watery all the way across the palate. Although there is plenty of bitter here, it just doesnt latch on. Not bad; Id drink it again.

12oz. bottle. Deep gold in color, with a very active head. Lots of lacing left by this one. Strongly floral nose. Nicely balanced hop profile is a little stronger than the typical APA, but isnt a monster. The palate is hit from front to back, so it does pair well with spicy foods. Nicely done beer.

12oz. bottle. Crystal clear gold pour. Tremendous head drops into an even white cap and leaves lots of lace. Really a beautiful looking beer. Aroma is strong on grass notes, backed up with sprucy pine and some honey sweetness. Tangy sweetness on the front of the tongue, but a little light on hop bite, which I was admittedly expecting. Still, its quite a pleasant beer, and Im glad to see this label branch out and shake things up a bit.

12oz. bottle. Sparkling honey gold; head dissipates rapidly with no lacing. Nose is mostly of grains, though there are some herbal/grass notes as well. Fresh, clean taste, again mostly grain. Good balance between malts and hops. Almost falls into the lawnmower beer class, but this is a slight cut above that. Alaskan Summer is also a great beer to entice friends out of the macrobrew rut.
